    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4187217454" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4187217454" />
    <a title="Michael Brown" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/49730449-michael-brown"><img alt="Michael Brown" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4187217454?book_show_action=true">Dec 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Brown" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Brown" href="/user/show/49730449-michael-brown">Michael Brown</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4187217454" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13210052811959482800">This is a book about the March on the Pentagon, a mass protest against the Vietnam War that took place on 21 October 1967. This was one of the largest (perhaps the largest?) US domestic protests against the War up until this time. In retrospect, it has been seen as an important historical moment, when sentiments against and for the War began to really harden, when the body politic began to fracture and polarise. The following year brought far more violent protests, but perhaps the seeds were sow</span>
  <span id="freeText13210052811959482800" style="display:none">This is a book about the March on the Pentagon, a mass protest against the Vietnam War that took place on 21 October 1967. This was one of the largest (perhaps the largest?) US domestic protests against the War up until this time. In retrospect, it has been seen as an important historical moment, when sentiments against and for the War began to really harden, when the body politic began to fracture and polarise. The following year brought far more violent protests, but perhaps the seeds were sown here.<br /><br />Norman Mailer was at the March and produced this remarkable account.<br /><br />The first part, 'History as Novel', covers his own personal experience of the March, including lead-up events in Washington DC and then being arrested in the advance upon the Pentagon building, then the custodial and legal processes that followed. Much of this part features what's going on in Mailer's own head, reflecting upon why he is there in the first place. There's considerable wry humour in how he depicts himself in the third-person as a character called "Mailer". While against the War, "Mailer" also seems motivated by an egotistical urge to be in the spotlight, competitively positioning himself alongside other notables such as his friend the poet Robert Lowell. "Mailer" also ponders the motives of the soldiers who lined up to defend the Pentagon and the various Left factions involved. The second part, 'Novel as History', is ostensibly a more objective account of events, drawn from a wide range of media and inside sources.<br /><br />The structure works well. Mailer's relatively early arrest means he missed the main protest action, but there is a suspenseful courtroom showdown with a judge who wants to make an example of him. Then the second half includes an account of what he missed. The brutal treatment of protesters by US soldiers and MPs becomes a gripping climax. The structure also makes the point that subjective experience can be factually valuable in such a situation, while supposedly "objective" reportage can feature a lot of bias and interpretation.<br /><br />Throughout, Mailer teases out how the March enacted a range of intricate macro-conflicts going on in the US, relating to class, race, gender, generational divides, urban-vs-rural, liberal-vs-conservative, tradition-vs-counterculture. His background means he quite a grasp on this terrain, having been a soldier in WWII, but also a radical social critic post-War, and self-professed "Left conservative".<br /><br />Here is a passage that stuck with me:<br /><br /><blockquote>A generation of American young had come along different from five previous generations of the middle class. The new generation believed in technology more than any before it, but the generation also believed in LSD, in witches, in tribal knowledge, in orgy, and revolution. It had no respect whatsoever for the unassailable logic of the next step: belief was reserved for the revelatory mystery of the happening where you did not know what was going to happen next; that was what was good about it. Their radicalism was in their hate for the authority - the authority was the manifest of evil to this generation. It was the the authority who had covered the land with those suburbs where they stifled as children while watching the adventures of the West in the movies, while looking at the guardians of dull genial celebrity on television; they had had their minds jabbed and poked and twitched and probed and finally galvanised into surrealistic modes of response by commercials cutting into dramatic narratives, and parents flipping from network to network - they were forced willy-nilly to build their own idea of the space-time continuum (and therefore their nervous systems) on the jumps and cracks and leaps and breaks which every phenomenon from the media seemed to contain within it.</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="13210052811959482800" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

